liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market has fallen deeper into the red in afternoon trade. It's down around three quarters of a percent in the last hour of trade with most sectors lower. Leading the losses are technology, industrials, consumer firms, and telecommunications. Packaging firm Orora is taking a hit because of plans to raise $1.35 billion in a discounted share placement to fund its purchase of French glass bottle maker Saverglass. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Some other economic data out today. Employment website Seek says job ads fell by 1.8 per cent in August from July, and they are down by nearly one fifth over the year. Applications per job increased by 6.5 per cent in August. That continues the trend we've been seeing for awhile after job ads peaked at record highs last year. More migration and a slowing economy means employers have more workers to chose from. Here's Seek managing director Kendra Banks: “After a slight rise in July, job ads declined 1.8 per cent in August driven by a drop in volumes in New South Wales. “Victoria and the Northern Territory were the only states to buck the trend, with regional job ad volumes in Victoria driving overall job ads up for the state, particularly those in retail & consumer products. "Ads for retail & consumer products roles rose nationally for the second month, as businesses begin preparing for the Christmas season." “Applications per job ad continue to rise, and after six months of growth, levels are now higher than they were in July 2019, demonstrating that competition for jobs is greater than it was pre-COVID." However, demand for labour is still strong with the unemployment near fifty year lows of 3.7 per cent in July. Hospitality and tourism job ads were down by 3.1 per cent in August and they are down by nearly 41 per cent over the year, which suggests new migrants and international students are filling more of these jobs.

“Applications per job ad continue to rise, and after six months of growth, levels are now higher than they were in July 2019, demonstrating that competition for jobs is greater than it was pre-COVID."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Not surprisingly Treasurer Jim Chalmers has given an upbeat response to the latest GDP figures, despite warning about the uncertainty faced by the Australian economy because of higher interest rates and a slowing China. The rise of 0.4 per cent over the June quarter, matched a 0.4 per cent increase over the March quarter. However growth pulled back over the year to June with the economy expanding by 2.1 per cent. Here's what Mr Chalmers had to say: "The Australian economy remains steady and sturdy in the face of unrelenting pressure." "Economic growth held up well despite the inevitable toll of higher interest rates, moderating inflation and continuing global uncertainty particularly as it relates to China." "We know that there are challenges ahead but we face them from a position of relative strength." Mr Chalmers noted that the high cost of living is weighing on consumers with housing spending growing by just 0.1 per cent over the quarter. "Australians continue to pull back on discretionary spending to make room for essentials and also to cover mortgage repayments." "People are also spending less on renovating their homes and are saving less out of their incomes." "We expect the economy to slow considerably over the next year and we expect the unemployment rate to tick up as well."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Treasurer says economy remains "steady and sturdy"
